comments.content: actually, ¬ªdespite¬´ isn‚Äôt even the right word here. the complement of a **soq** serial can be attributive or predicative. if it‚Äôs predicative (say, A B), then **soq** sees the property of satisfying A the most (while also being B); if attributive, we still get valid semantics for things like **nuƒ± k·∫£nƒ±** ‚Äòsmall rabbit‚Äô, since the **nuƒ±**-est **k·∫£nƒ±** is also the **nuƒ±**-est thing that is also a **kanƒ±**

comments.content: in other words, since the extent of an adjectival serial A B is proportional to the extent of A and not A √ó B (barring situations where B is flat-out false), **soq** will look at the correct ¬ªpart¬´ of the serial

comments.content: yet another way to look at it: in an adjectival serial such as A B, the A part is qualitative (how *much* something is A), whereas the B part is quantitative (*if* that thing is B *at all*). so rather than A √ó B we have something like the *truth value* of B times the *extent* of Aa
